### Stage -1 — Requirement Vetting
- **Owner:** Requester/PM, with AI doing the legwork before the PRD is drafted.
- **Activity:** Before a PRD is written, check the raw idea against: the actual codebase (does this already exist, partially exist, or conflict with existing code?), past similar stories/tickets (was this tried or explicitly rejected before, and why?), and platform facts (known capacity constraints, roadmap conflicts, standing ADR decisions this would contradict). This exists because a PRD locks in a problem statement and acceptance criteria — if the premise is already flawed, every downstream stage inherits a clean-looking document built on a bad foundation.
- **Artifact:** Vetting Note — short, attached to the idea ticket: prior art found, related past tickets and their outcomes, relevant platform constraints, and any direct conflicts with existing ADRs.
- **Gate:** PM reviews the Vetting Note before Stage 0 starts. If it surfaces something that should change the ask (already exists, was rejected for a still-valid reason, conflicts with a roadmap commitment), that gets resolved here — not discovered mid-Design-Review three stages later.

### Stage 0 — Intake & PRD
- **Owner:** Requester/PM drives intake; PM is accountable for the finalized PRD.
- **Activity:** AI agent drafts a full PRD from the initial idea/ask **and the Stage -1 Vetting Note** — problem statement, target user/business context, requirements, explicit acceptance criteria, success metrics, and **explicit non-goals** (what this is deliberately not solving, so scope doesn't silently expand later). Any prior art, past-rejection context, or platform constraint surfaced in vetting gets reflected directly in the PRD (e.g. as a non-goal, or as a note on why this differs from the prior attempt). PM reviews, corrects, and finalizes — same pattern as Stage 2-Draft: the draft removes the blank-page problem, the PM remains accountable for what the org commits to building.
- **Artifact:** PRD (Confluence template) — this is what Stage 1 and Stage 2-Draft actually read, not a one-line ticket summary. Linked Jira Epic carries the PRD link, not a duplicate of its content.
- **Gate:** PM/EM assigns an initial Risk Tier based on the PRD (can be revised at Stage 1). Nothing moves to Discovery without a tier and an approved PRD.
- *Tier 1 uses a lightweight version: problem + acceptance criteria, no full PRD template — see §3.*

### Stage 1 — Discovery & System Impact Analysis
- **Owner:** Tech lead/architect assigned to the idea, plus owners of any service suspected to be affected.
- **Activity:** Map every service, data flow, API/event contract, **and infrastructure dependency** (new/changed compute, queues/topics, env vars, IAM/permissions, network rules) the approved PRD's requirements touch — upstream and downstream — and flag any **new external/third-party dependency** (new package, new SaaS integration) likely needed. This is the direct fix for "incidents from missed system impact." Infra changes and new external dependencies are flagged here explicitly because they're easy to miss if the analysis only looks at internal services, and they carry their own license/supply-chain/compliance review needs.
- **Artifact:** "System Impact Map" (Confluence template) — services touched, owning teams, integration points, infra/IaC touched, blast-radius notes.
- **Gate (Tier 2/3):** Each affected service owner acknowledges the map (a comment/checkbox is enough — the point is they can't be surprised later). **If infra/IaC is touched, platform/SRE team is added as an acknowledging owner.**
- *Tier 1 skips this stage entirely.*

### Stage 1.5 — Dependency Coordination (Early Heads-Up)
- **Owner:** Tech lead/architect who ran Stage 1, addressed to the owning lead of each dependent team identified in the Impact Map.
- **Activity:** For every cross-team dependency the Impact Map found, send a structured early-warning notice — rough shape of what's needed, why, and roughly when — *before* design work locks in scope. This is deliberately lightweight: it exists so a dependent team's lead isn't blindsided three sprints later by a fully-formed ask they have zero capacity for. It is not yet a commitment request.
- **Artifact:** Dependency Notice per affected team — what's likely needed, rough timing, who to talk to if this conflicts with their existing roadmap.
- **Gate:** Each notified team lead acknowledges receipt (not commitment) within an agreed SLA (e.g. 2 business days). A non-response after the SLA escalates to both tech leads' managers — silence is not a yes, but it also can't be allowed to silently stall the requesting team.

### Stage 2 — Design & NFR Definition
- **Owner:** Tech lead/architect (matches your existing ownership model).
- **Activity:** AI agent (Claude Code, with repo + Stage 1 Impact Map access) produces a first full draft of the Design Doc, tagging each section as grounded-in-code, inferred, or "needs architect decision." Architect reviews, corrects, and finalizes — the architect remains accountable for the design; the draft just removes the blank-page problem and front-loads the codebase research. Final doc (Confluence template) covers: problem, proposed approach, alternatives considered and rejected, data model changes (or explicitly "none"), and a **mandatory NFR section**:
  - Performance/latency target
  - Expected load & scalability ceiling
  - Availability/SLA expectation
  - Security & data classification
  - Observability plan (what gets logged/alerted)
  - Backward compatibility / migration plan
  - Cost impact (infra spend)
- **If data model changes are involved:** this routes into your existing formal schema review — keep that process as-is, just make it a tracked, mandatory sub-step here so it stops being inconsistent.
- **Artifact:** Approved Design Doc + an ADR (Architecture Decision Record) entry for any consequential decision, so "why we did it this way" survives staff turnover.
- **Gate (Tier 2/3):** Architecture review sign-off, recorded in Confluence/Jira. **Tier 3 in your regulated context adds a Security/Compliance reviewer to this same gate** — this is what produces your audit trail, for free, at the point the decision is actually made.

### Stage 2d — Test Strategy
- **Owner:** Tech lead/architect, with input from QA.
- **Activity:** Before any code is written, decide what kind of testing this specific change needs and at what pyramid layer — unit, integration, contract (for every cross-service boundary in the Stage 1 Impact Map), end-to-end, and a concrete verification method for each NFR target from Stage 2 (load test for performance, security scan for the security target, etc.). This is a deliberate, separate step because "write tests" left implicit defaults to thin unit coverage and skips exactly the cross-service contract tests this workflow exists to enforce.
- **Artifact:** Test Strategy doc — test pyramid table, NFR-to-verification-method mapping, explicit out-of-scope notes, and any standing contract-test gaps surfaced along the way.
- **Gate (Tier 2/3):** Test plan reviewed alongside the Design Doc — implementation does not start until both are approved together.

### Stage 2e — Story Creation
- **Owner:** Tech lead/architect drafts via AI; engineer (or PM, for user-facing acceptance criteria) confirms before work starts.
- **Activity:** AI agent breaks the approved Design Doc and Test Strategy into Jira stories/tasks. Each story is a **vertical slice** — it cuts through every layer the feature touches end-to-end (UI/API/service/data, as applicable), not a horizontal slice of a single layer — with explicit acceptance criteria traceable back to a specific PRD requirement and a specific part of the design, not generic restatements of the design doc. Each story should be implementable on its own without the engineer (or implementing AI agent) needing to re-derive scope from the design doc from scratch. This exists because "design is broken into stories" left implicit was producing vague, horizontally-sliced stories that an AI implementer would fill gaps in with assumptions instead of flagging — the same failure mode Stage 3-Implement's "stop and ask" instruction exists to prevent, just one step earlier.
- **HITL/AFK tagging:** Every story is tagged **HITL** (Human-In-The-Loop — requires a human decision point, such as an architectural judgment call, ambiguous UX decision, or anything Stage 1/2 flagged as an open question) or **AFK** (Away-From-Keyboard — implementable and mergeable through Stage 3/4 without a human decision mid-stream; the human merge gate at Stage 3 still applies regardless). This tag is what lets you actually run Tier 2/3 work through AI implementation efficiently: AFK stories queue straight into Stage 3-Implement, HITL stories get routed to a human decision first so the implementing agent isn't left guessing.
- **Artifact:** Jira stories/tasks, each linked to: the PRD requirement it satisfies, the Design Doc section it implements, the Test Strategy layer(s) it's responsible for, and its HITL/AFK tag.
- **Gate (Tier 2/3):** Engineer/PM confirms the story breakdown actually covers the full design (nothing dropped), doesn't introduce scope the design didn't approve (nothing added), is sliced vertically rather than by layer, and has a sensible HITL/AFK tag before Stage 3 begins.

### Stage 2e.5 — Dependency Coordination (Firm Ask)
- **Owner:** Tech lead/architect, addressed to the owning lead of each dependent team.
- **Activity:** Now that stories exist, convert each Stage 1.5 heads-up into a specific, answerable ask: exactly which stories depend on the other team, exactly what's needed from them (an API contract, a schema change, a feature flag, capacity on their sprint), and a proposed target sprint/date. The ask is written so the other team's lead can say yes, no, or "not until sprint X" without needing a meeting just to understand the question.
- **Artifact:** Dependency Request per affected team, structured as: what we need, by when, what happens if it slips (impact on our timeline), and an explicit question set (see prompts file) rather than an open-ended ask.
- **Gate (Tier 2/3):** Each dependent team lead responds with one of: **Committed** (date confirmed, capacity allocated), **Conditional** (date possible if X happens first — name X), or **Conflict** (can't meet this without something else slipping — name what). "Conflict" responses escalate to both teams' managers for prioritization; they don't just sit unresolved. No story that depends on an uncommitted external team proceeds past this gate as AFK — it's auto-tagged HITL regardless of what Stage 2e said, since "wait for another team" is exactly the kind of mid-stream decision AFK is supposed to exclude.

### Stage 3 — Implementation
- **Owner:** Engineering team (accountable for the result; AI agent does the initial writing).
- **Activity:** **AFK-tagged** stories from Stage 2e queue straight into implementation; **HITL-tagged** stories get their flagged decision resolved by a human first, then proceed the same way. An AI agent (Claude Code, with repo access) implements the Stage 2e stories one at a time, against the approved Design Doc, building tests exactly to the layers scoped in the Stage 2d Test Strategy (not inventing test scope on the fly), and stopping to flag anything underspecified rather than guessing — including flagging a story that turns out to need a human decision the HITL/AFK tag didn't anticipate. A **different** AI session reviews the diff against the design/NFRs/security (Stage 3 review + Stage 3-Security prompts) — never the same session that wrote the code, since it shares the same blind spots.
- **Gate (all tiers, no exceptions):** A human engineer must explicitly approve the PR before merge. "AI writes the implementation" does not mean AI merges it — the engineer reviewing is the named, accountable approver of record, the same as if a junior engineer had opened the PR. This approval is what the audit trail actually points to; an AI review pass is supporting evidence, not the approval itself.
- **Gate (Tier 3, recommended Tier 2 touching auth/data access):** Code-level security review (distinct from the design-level security sign-off at Stage 2) — a design can be approved as secure and the implementation can still introduce a vulnerability the design never specified at that granularity.
- **Practice:** Short-lived branches, feature flags for anything that won't be release-ready by the next train, so trunk stays deployable. Branch protection enforces the human-approval gate technically, not just procedurally.

### Stage 4 — Verification & NFR Validation
- **Owner:** Engineering + QA.
- **Activity:** Functional tests, plus explicit validation against the NFR targets set in Stage 2 (load test, security scan, etc.) and the test pyramid layers scoped in Stage 2d — confirm every layer the plan called for (unit/integration/contract/e2e) actually shows up in the diff, not just whichever was easiest to write. **Tier 3 requires attached evidence** before sign-off — this is the fix for "NFRs discovered too late."
- **Artifact:** Test evidence attached directly to the Jira ticket.

### Stage 5 — Release Readiness & Change Approval
- **Owner:** Release manager (lightweight CAB — appropriate given regulated + scheduled releases).
- **Activity:** Before each release train, a short review of what's going out: tier, rollback plan, who approved each item. Tier 1 = simple checklist. Tier 2/3 = explicit recorded sign-off.
- **Artifact:** Release Record (Confluence page) — this is the page an auditor gets pointed to. It links idea → design approval → impact map → test evidence → this approval, end to end.

### Stage 6 — Deploy & Post-Release Validation
- **Owner:** Engineering/SRE.
- **Activity:** Deploy with the release train, watch the dashboards defined in the NFR section, explicit rollback trigger defined in advance (not improvised mid-incident).
- **Artifact:** Post-release health check sign-off within 24–48h.

### Stage 7 — Retrospective
- **Owner:** PM/Tech lead.
- **Activity (Tier 3, any incident, or emergency change):** Did the actual impact match the predicted impact? Was anything missed? Feed it back into the Impact Map template or the tiering rules themselves. This is what makes the process improve instead of calcify.
- **Activity (Tier 1/2 — sampled, not every change):** Periodically (e.g. one in N Tier 2 changes per sprint, picked at random rather than self-selected) run the same predicted-vs-actual check. Tier 3 work is rare and high-stakes, but it's also a biased sample — if you only ever learn from your riskiest changes, you'll never catch the patterns that show up in your much more frequent Tier 1/2 work. This sampling is what keeps the tiering rules honest instead of just reinforcing whatever Tier 3 happened to teach you.

