## 3. Tier 1 Fast Path

To make sure the rigor above doesn't slow down trivial work, Tier 1 changes get a deliberately thin path: a quick prior-art check (does this already exist — a single search, not a full Vetting Note) → ticket with problem + acceptance criteria (no full PRD) → PR (linked to ticket, no design doc, story breakdown, or separate test strategy required — engineer/agent uses standard test conventions for the area) → standard tests → merge → included in next release's checklist as a single line item. No formal vetting note, no impact map, no design doc, no test strategy doc, no separate story-creation step, no extra sign-off. If a "Tier 1" change turns out to touch the data model or cross a service boundary once someone's in the code, it gets auto-bumped to Tier 2 before merge — that's a process bug to fix, not an exception to quietly allow.

---

## 3.5 Emergency Change Path

Scheduled release trains are right for planned work, but production incidents don't wait for the next train. Without an explicit emergency path, people will go around this process during exactly the moments when bypassing it is most dangerous — and your audit trail will have a hole at the worst possible time. This path exists so "emergency" stays an exception with its own record, not an unofficial way to skip the process whenever something feels urgent.

- **Trigger:** Active production incident or a fix that genuinely cannot wait for the next release train (defined narrowly — "we want this faster" is not an emergency; this is for active customer/data impact).
- **Process:** Incident commander or on-call lead declares an emergency change. Fix is implemented and reviewed with whatever subset of Stages 3/3-Security/4 is actually feasible in the time available — but never skips the human merge gate or, for anything touching auth/data/schema, the security review (Stage 3-Security). What gets compressed is ceremony (async sign-offs, full design doc), not the safety-critical checks themselves.
- **Approval:** A single accountable approver (on-call lead/incident commander) can approve in the moment; this is recorded immediately, not retroactively reconstructed.
- **Mandatory follow-up:** Within 48 hours, the change gets a retroactive Stage 1 Impact Map and Stage 5-equivalent Release Record filed — same artifacts as planned work, just sequenced after the fact instead of before. This keeps the audit trail complete and feeds Stage 7 (Retrospective) the same way an incident always should.
- **Tracking:** Emergency changes are tagged distinctly in Jira and reported on separately — if this path gets used often, that's a signal your release cadence or Tier 1 fast path needs adjusting, not that the emergency path is working as intended.

