## 6. How This Maps to Your Stated Drivers

| Driver you flagged | Mechanism that addresses it |
|---|---|
| Incidents from missed system impact | Mandatory Impact Map + service-owner sign-off (Stage 1) |
| Cross-team work stalling or surprising dependent teams | Two-touch dependency coordination — early heads-up (Stage 1.5) before scope locks, firm ask with explicit Committed/Conditional/Conflict response (Stage 2e.5) before implementation starts; uncommitted dependencies auto-force a story to HITL regardless of its original tag |
| Mismatch between idea and what's built | Requirement vetting (Stage -1) catches a flawed premise before it's locked into acceptance criteria; PRD with explicit acceptance criteria and non-goals (Stage 0) then carries through as traceable links on every story (Stage 2e) back to the specific requirement it satisfies |
| Wasted dev cycles on already-solved or previously-rejected work | Stage -1 checks the codebase, past similar tickets, and platform constraints before any design work starts — this is the cheapest stage to fail fast in, by design |
| NFRs discovered too late | NFRs are a required section of the Design Doc, mapped to a concrete verification method in Stage 2d, validated with evidence before release (Stage 2, 2d & 4) |
| Thin/inconsistent test coverage, especially cross-service | Stage 2d makes the test pyramid an explicit, reviewed plan — contract tests for every cross-service boundary are a named requirement, not an assumption |
| Audit trail / compliance | Every gate is a timestamped, named approval already living in Jira/Confluence — no separate audit-prep work; emergency changes get the same artifacts filed retroactively within 48h |
| Faster dev cycle | Risk tiering + Tier 1 fast path mean only genuinely risky work pays the full process cost; HITL/AFK tagging at Stage 2e means most Tier 2/3 stories also move at AI speed, with humans only pulled in for the subset that genuinely needs a decision |
| AI writing code without losing accountability | Explicit human merge gate at every tier (Stage 3), code-level security review separate from design-level (Stage 3-Security), and sampled human re-checks of AI output (§7 rollout metrics) keep a person accountable throughout |

