# Part 2 — AI Skills

Built for **Claude Code** (or an equivalent agent with filesystem/repo access). Each skill is self-contained: it names the artifacts it needs as input and the artifact it produces, not a position in a sequence. Run them in whatever order your situation calls for — a skill that needs something you don't have yet will say so in its output rather than silently guessing.

**How to use these:**
- Each skill lists **Requires** (artifacts it needs, by name) and **Produces** (the artifact it creates). If you don't have a required artifact yet, run the skill that produces it first — but nothing here assumes a fixed order beyond that basic dependency logic.
- Every skill ends with a **required output format** — keep that, so findings can be pasted straight into Jira/Confluence and stay consistent reviewer-to-reviewer.
- Every skill includes a grounding instruction (don't speculate, read the actual files) — this is what makes the difference between a real review and a generic one.
- **Cross-team dependencies get two touches, not one:** `dependency-heads-up` is a lightweight early heads-up (no commitment expected, just acknowledgment and an early conflict flag), sent as soon as a System Impact Map exists. `dependency-firm-ask` is the firm ask (Committed/Conditional/Conflict, forced choice), sent once concrete stories exist. The gap between these exists on purpose — asking for a firm commitment before scope is real just produces a guess dressed up as a date.
- A Design Doc has two parts: `design-doc-generation` produces the first draft, `design-review` / `nfr-review` / `data-model-review` / `test-strategy` each review and plan against it from a different angle. The architect is accountable for the final design either way — the draft just removes the blank-page problem and front-loads the codebase research.
- `test-strategy` decides *what kind* of testing a change needs — and at what pyramid layer — before implementation starts. This exists precisely because "write tests" left implicit defaults to thin unit-test coverage and skips the cross-service contract tests that actually catch the failures this whole set of skills is designed to prevent.
- `story-creation` slices vertically (each story cuts end-to-end through every layer it touches, never isolated to one layer) and tags every story **HITL** (needs a human decision first) or **AFK** (fully specified, can go straight to AI implementation). This is what lets most work move through AI implementation efficiently without quietly trading rigor for speed — AFK stories don't wait on anyone, HITL stories get a human decision before the implementing agent would otherwise have to guess.
- Implementation has three review angles, run as separate sessions from the implementing agent and from each other: correctness/conformance (`implementation-review`), security at the code level (`security-review` — distinct from `design-review`'s security input, since secure designs can still have insecure implementations), and infrastructure/IaC where applicable (`infra-review`). None of these substitute for a human merge gate — they're evidence the human approver uses, not the approval itself.

